---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import ReplyTask from '../../../../../components/ReplyTask.astro';
import SessionPage from '../../../../../components/SessionPage.astro';
import SessionSection from '../../../../../components/SessionSection.astro';

const modelCode = `public record Score(string Player, int Points);

var score = new Score("Iris", 12);
var points = score.Points;`;

const replyText = `[learn:csharp/007:q1]

Use this syntax model. Its names are different from your task:

public record Score(string Player, int Points);
var score = new Score("Iris", 12);
var points = score.Points;

Your specification:
- Type name: WorkshopSignupRequest
- AttendeeName: string
- SeatCount: int
- Note: string?
- Keep this exact field order.
- Construct a value named signup with "Maya", 2, and null.
- Read the generated SeatCount property into a variable named seats.

Write exactly three C# lines: one declaration, one new expression assigned to signup, and one property read assigned to seats. Do not write a class, method, full program, attributes, validation, or extra code.

A. Public positional record declaration:
Answer:

B. Construction assigned to signup:
Answer:

C. SeatCount property read assigned to seats:
Answer:`;
---

<SessionPage
  title="Session 7 · C#: compact request model"
  heading="Declare, construct, and read one positional record"
  lede="Turn a small three-field specification into one compact C# request model, then use the generated properties."
  backHref="/topics/csharp/"
  backLabel="C# sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="The three-line pattern">
    <p>A positional record puts the type name and its property list on one line. Each item in the list creates a public property with the same name and type.</p>
    <Code code={modelCode} lang="csharp" />
    <ol>
      <li>The first line declares the record.</li>
      <li>The second line constructs one value. The values follow the declared order.</li>
      <li>The third line reads one generated property with <code>value.PropertyName</code>.</li>
    </ol>
    <Callout>
      <code>string?</code> means the value may be a string or <code>null</code>. It does not remove that position from the constructor. You still supply all three values in this task.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Your supplied specification">
    <p>Declare <code>WorkshopSignupRequest</code> with these positions, in this exact order:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><code>AttendeeName</code> — <code>string</code></li>
      <li><code>SeatCount</code> — <code>int</code></li>
      <li><code>Note</code> — <code>string?</code></li>
    </ol>
    <p>Then create <code>signup</code> with <code>"Maya"</code>, <code>2</code>, and <code>null</code>. Read <code>SeatCount</code> into <code>seats</code>.</p>
  </SessionSection>

  <ReplyTask id="learn:csharp/007:q1" copyText={replyText} difficulty={3}>
    <p><strong>Write exactly three C# lines.</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li>Write the public positional record declaration.</li>
      <li>Construct <code>signup</code> with the supplied values.</li>
      <li>Read <code>signup.SeatCount</code> into <code>seats</code>.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Do not write a class, method, full program, attributes, validation, or extra code.</p>
  </ReplyTask>
</SessionPage>
